node.text: Classic Chinese and French methods for steaming fish produce moist, flavorful results. We used the best of both approaches to come up with an entirely new method that's easy and equally impressive. Get our Oven-Steamed Fish with Scallions and Ginger recipe by clicking the link in our profile.

node.text: Less common (and less expensive) than leg of lamb, a lamb shoulder roast is an intensely flavorful cut. It's ideal for slow braising, which produces fall-apart tender meat. Our version uses figs, which creates a sauce that had a great balance of salty, sweet, and tart notes. Spiced Lamb Pot Roast with Figs recipe link in bio.

node.text: For decades, the lobster roll has been at the center of one of the Eastern Seaboard’s most fervent food debates. What side are you on? Let us know if you’re #TeamButter or #TeamMayo in the comments below and tap the link in our profile to learn more.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by America's Test Kitchen on September 03, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: Grain salads are a heartier alternative to lettuce-based ones, but often require more time and work. Not so here. In this bright-yet-smoky, sweet-yet-tart riff on a grain salad, we used quick-cooking pearl couscous and toasted it with chorizo and a carrot, then stirred in broth with some smoked paprika and cumin. We added pantry-friendly chickpeas for heft, and parsley (or cilantro) added a punch of freshness. Get our Warm Spiced Couscous Salad for One recipe by clicking the link in our profile.
